		<img width="2500" height="1200" src="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-deep-sea-mining-1.jpg" class="singlepostthumb wp-post-image" alt="" decoding="async" fetchpriority="high" srcset="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-deep-sea-mining-1.jpg 2500w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-deep-sea-mining-1-520x250.jpg 520w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-deep-sea-mining-1-1200x576.jpg 1200w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-deep-sea-mining-1-768x369.jpg 768w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-deep-sea-mining-1-1536x737.jpg 1536w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-deep-sea-mining-1-2048x983.jpg 2048w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-deep-sea-mining-1-900x432.jpg 900w" sizes="(max-width: 2500px) 100vw, 2500px" /><div class="post-thumbnail-caption">The current targets of deep-sea mining are the polymetallic nodules that lay on the seafloor in some locations. Scientists have known about these nodules since the HMS <em>Challenger</em> expedition in the 1870s. Photo by Science History Images/Alamy Stock Photo</div>
			<article class="main container col4">
								<header class="maincol">
										<h1 class="pagetitle">What’s Next for Deep-Sea Mining?</h1>
										<h2 class="dek singlepagecontainer">With mining applications on the horizon, the International Seabed Authority’s crucial Mining Code is still far from finished.</h2>
										<section class="singlebyline singlepagecontainer">
						<h3 class="invis">Authored by</h3>
						by  
										<a href="https://hakaimagazine.com/profiles/elham-shabahat/" class="tagmanager" id="author_link_top" >Elham Shabahat</a>								<br/>
												</section>
					 
					<aside class="singlebydatewords singlepagecontainer">
						<h3 class="invis">Wordcount</h3>
						December 18, 2024 | 850 words, about 4 minutes
					</aside>

					
